wed":1,"href":"http://grrm.livejournal.com/38501.html?thread=3551845#t3551845","name":"collapse","title":"Collapse"},{"allowed":1,"href":"http://grrm.livejournal.com/38501.html?thread=3551845#t3551845","name":"expand","title":"Expand"}],"uname":"ohilya","loaded":1,"p_tracked":0,"commenter_journal_base":"http://ohilya.livejournal.com/","statprefix":"http://l-stat.livejournal.net","dtalkid":3551845,"talkid":13874,"thread_url":"http://grrm.livejournal.com/38501.html?thread=3551845#t3551845","upictitle":"Ilya Popov: Acrobat","article":"George, is there *any* chance you could get Ellen and/or Gardner and/or Anne to come and talk a little bit about what it is editors do? What the day to day duties and responsibilities of an editor are, whether or not they use XML to edit manuscripts (or some other markup language), how they delegate editing responsibilities, etc etc. <br /><br />You have at least one reader who is relentlessly curious as to what their job encompasses, and what sort of relationship they have with writers such as yourself and how writers work with editors and editors with writers. <br />","siteroot":"http://www.livejournal.com","poster":"grrm","stime":"9 years ago","ctime":"February 25 2008, 08:08:54 UTC","massactions":0,"subject":"Can the editors come out to play?","deleted":0,"username":[{"journal_url":"http://ohilya.livejournal.com/","striked":null,"journaltype":"P","userhead_url":"http://l-stat.livejournal.net/img/userinfo_v8.svg?v=17080?v=146.10","color":null,"noctxpopup":0,"side_alias":0,"journal":"ohilya","inline_css":0,"attrs":null,"is_identity":0,"bold":1,"show_userhead":1,"username":"ohilya","user_alias":"","profile_url":"http://ohilya.livejournal.com/profile","alias":0}],"dname":"ohilya","ctime_ts":1203926934,"tracked":0},{"shown":1,"collapsed":0,"actions":[{"allowed":1,"href":"http://grrm.livejournal.com/38501.html?replyto=3572837","name":"reply","title":"Reply","footer":1},{"allowed":1,"href":"http://grrm.livejournal.com/38501.html?thread=3572837#t3572837","name":"permalink","title":"link"},{"allowed":1,"href":"http://grrm.livejournal.com/38501.html?thread=3572837#t3572837","name":"collapse","title":"Collapse"},{"allowed":1,"href":"http://grrm.livejournal.com/38501.html?thread=3572837#t3572837","name":"expand","title":"Expand"}],"uname":"akailaughingman","loaded":1,"p_tracked":0,"commenter_journal_base":"http://akailaughingman.livejournal.com/","statprefix":"http://l-stat.livejournal.net","dtalkid":3572837,"talkid":13956,"thread_url":"http://grrm.livejournal.com/38501.html?thread=3572837#t3572837","above":3551845,"upictitle":"akailaughingman: pic#0","article":"I know a copyeditor. They basically fact-check everything, edit for style (all the way down to musicality of language), grammar, and tell you when something is running too long, or when the reader has clear forgotten what color someone's eyes are (whether that's good or bad). They're also good at telling you which parts of your book suck, and when you need to make the whole thing tighter.<br /><br />From my experience, copyeditors like to use paper. That way it's easier to tell when they've burned a hole through your manuscript to say \"don't use that word ten times in a row.\"<br /><br />They are the glue that makes a good book. The author provides a good idea, a kernel, and the editor makes that idea shine.<br /><br />Props to Martin's editor -- seems the type to keep giving criticism, even after the author got big (which some editors -- RJ's in particular, are loathe to do).","siteroot":"http://www.livejournal.com","poster":"grrm","stime":"9 years ago","ctime":"March 4 2008, 20:25:31 UTC","parent":3551845,"massactions":0,"subject":"Re: Can the editors come out to play?","deleted":0,"username":[{"journal_url":"http://akailaughingman.livejournal.com/","striked":null,"journaltype":"P","userhead_url":"http://l-stat.livejournal.net/img/userinfo_v8.svg?v=17080?v=146.10","color":null,"noctxpopup":0,"side_alias":0,"journal":"akailaughingman","inline_css"